    <div id="section1" class="section">
        <h2>Section 1: Introduction</h2>
        <p>This is an introductory section with some text explaining the purpose of the document. HTML stands for HyperText Markup Language, and it's used to create web pages. It's the foundation of most websites and is the standard markup language for documents designed to be displayed in a web browser.</p>
    </div>

    <div id="section2" class="section">
        <h2>Section 2: HTML Structure</h2>
        <p>HTML documents have a simple structure. They are divided into various sections, each with its own purpose. Here's an example of a basic structure:</p>
        <pre>
&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html&gt;
    &lt;head&gt;
        &lt;title&gt;Page Title&lt;/title&gt;
    &lt;/head&gt;
    &lt;body&gt;
        &lt;h1&gt;This is a Heading&lt;/h1&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;This is a paragraph.&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;
        </pre>
        <p>This structure includes the <code>DOCTYPE</code> declaration, the <code>&lt;html&gt;</code> element, <code>&lt;head&gt;</code> for metadata, and <code>&lt;body&gt;</code> for the content.</p>
    </div>

    <div id="section3" class="section">
        <h2>Section 3: Forms</h2>
        <p>Forms in HTML allow users to input data. Here is an example of a simple form:</p>
        <form action="/submit" method="post">
            <label for="name">Name:</label><br>
            <input type="text" id="name" name="name"><br><br>
            <label for="email">Email:</label><br>
            <input type="email" id="email" name="email"><br><br>
            <label for="message">Message:</label><br>
            <textarea id="message" name="message" rows="4" cols="50"></textarea><br><br>
            <input type="submit" value="Submit">
        </form>
    </div>

